# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dicotyledon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Important structures in **plant development** are buds, shoots, roots, leaves, and flowers; plants produce these tissues and structures throughout their life from meristems located at the tips of organs, or between mature tissues.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Thus, a living plant always has embryonic tissues.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] By contrast, an animal embryo will very early produce all of the body parts that it will ever have in its life.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] When the animal is born (or hatches from its egg), it has all its body parts and from that point will only grow larger and more mature.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] However, both plants and animals pass through a phylotypic stage that evolved independently and that causes a developmental constraint limiting morphological diversification.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Carl Leopold, the properties of organization seen in a plant are emergent properties which are more than the sum of the individual parts.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] A vascular plant begins from a single celled zygote, formed by fertilisation of an egg cell by a sperm cell.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] From that point, it begins to divide to form a plant embryo through the process of **embryogenesis**.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] As this happens, the resulting cells will organize so that one end becomes the first root while the other end forms the tip of the shoot.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In seed plants, the embryo will develop one or more "seed leaves" (cotyledons).
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] By the end of embryogenesis, the young plant will have all the parts necessary to begin in its life.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Once the embryo germinates from its seed or parent plant, it begins to produce additional organs (leaves, stems, and roots) through the process of **organogenesis**.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] New roots grow from root meristems located at the tip of the root, and new stems and leaves grow from shoot meristems located at the tip of the shoot.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Branching occurs when small clumps of cells left behind by the meristem, and which have not yet undergone cellular differentiation to form a specialized tissue, begin to grow as the tip of a new root or shoot.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Growth from any such meristem at the tip of a root or shoot is termed primary growth and results in the lengthening of that root or shoot.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Secondary growth results in widening of a root or shoot from divisions of cells in a cambium.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Direct organogenesis is a method of plant tissue culture in which organs like roots and shoots develop directly from meristematic or non-meristematic cells, bypassing the callus formation stage.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This process takes place through the activation of shoot and root apical meristems or axillary buds, influenced by internal or externally applied plant growth regulators.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] As a result, specific cell types differentiate to form plant structures that can grow into whole plants.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This technique is commonly used for propagating various plant species, including vegetables, fruits, woody plants, and medicinal plants.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Shoot tips and nodal segments are typically used as explants in this process.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In some cases, adventitious structures arise from somatic tissues under specific conditions, allowing for the regeneration of shoots or roots in areas where they would not naturally develop.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This approach is particularly effective in herbaceous species, and while adventitious regeneration can lead to a higher rate of shoot formation, axillary shoot proliferation remains the most widely used method in micropropagation due to its efficiency and practicality.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The general sequence of organ development in this process follows the pattern: Primary Explant → Meristemoid → Organ Primordium.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Indirect organogenesis is a developmental process in which plant cells undergo dedifferentiation, allowing them to revert from their specialized state and transition into a new developmental pathway.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This process is characterized by an intermediate callus stage, where cells lose their original identity and become morphologically adaptable, serving as the foundation for organ formation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The progression of indirect organogenesis involves several key phases, beginning with dedifferentiation, which enables the cells to attain competence, followed by an induction stage that leads to a fully determined state.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Once determination is achieved, the cells undergo morphological changes, ultimately giving rise to functional shoots or roots.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This process follows a structured developmental sequence: Primary Explant → Callus → Meristemoid → Organ Primordium, ensuring the organized formation of plant organs.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The ability to regenerate plants successfully depends on selecting the right explant, which varies among species and plant varieties.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In direct organogenesis, explants sourced from meristematic tissues, such as shoot tips, lateral buds, leaves, petioles, roots, and floral structures, are often preferred due to their ability to rapidly develop into new organs.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] These tissues have high survival rates, fast growth, and strong regenerative potential in vitro.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Meristems, shoot tips, axillary buds, immature leaves, and embryos are particularly effective in promoting regeneration across a wide range of plant species.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Additionally, mature plant parts, including leaves, stems, roots, petioles, and flower segments, can also serve as viable explants for organ formation under suitable conditions.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Plant regeneration occurs through the formation of callus, an undifferentiated mass of cells that later gives rise to new organs.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Callus formation can be induced from various explants, such as cotyledons, hypocotyls, stems, leaves, shoot apices, roots, inflorescences, and floral structures, when cultured under controlled conditions.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Generally, explants containing actively dividing cells are more effective for callus initiation, as they have a higher capacity for cellular reprogramming.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Immature tissues tend to be more adaptable for regeneration compared to mature tissues due to their increased developmental plasticity.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The size and shape of the explant also influence the success of culture establishment, as larger or more structurally favorable explants may enhance the chances of survival and growth.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Callus development is primarily triggered by wounding and the presence of plant hormones, which may be naturally present in the tissue or supplemented in the growth medium to stimulate cellular activity and organ formation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Culture media compositions vary significantly in their mineral elements and vitamin content to accommodate diverse plant species requirements.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Murashige and Skoog (MS) medium is distinguished by its high nitrogen content in ammonium form, a characteristic not found in other formulations.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Sucrose typically serves as the primary carbohydrate source across various media types.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The interaction between auxins and cytokinins in regulating organogenesis is well-established, though responses vary by species.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Some plants, such as tobacco, can spontaneously form shoot buds without exogenous growth regulators, while others like *Scurrula pulverulenta*, *Lactuca sativa*, and *Brassica juncea* strictly require hormonal supplementation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In *B. juncea* cotyledon cultures, benzylaminopurine (BAP) alone induces shoot formation from petiole tissue, similar to radiata pine where cytokinin alone suffices for shoot induction.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Research indicates that endogenous hormone concentrations, rather than exogenous application levels, ultimately determine organogenic differentiation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Among the various cytokinins (2iP, BAP, thidiazuron, kinetin, and zeatin) used for shoot induction, BAP has demonstrated superior efficacy and widespread application.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Auxins similarly influence organogenic pathways, with 2,4-D commonly used for callus induction in cereals, though organogenesis typically requires transfer to media containing IAA or NAA or lacking 2,4-D entirely.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The auxin-to-cytokinin ratio largely determines which organs develop.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Gibberellic acid (GA3) contributes to cell elongation and meristemoid formation, while unconventional compounds like tri-iodobenzoic acid (TIBA), abscisic acid (ABA), kanamycin, and auxin inhibitors have proven effective for recalcitrant species.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Natural additives like ginseng powder can enhance regeneration frequency in certain cultures.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Since ethylene typically suppresses shoot differentiation, inhibitors of ethylene synthesis such as aminoethoxyvinylglycine (AVG) and silver nitrate (AgNO3) are often employed to promote organogenesis, with documented success in wheat, tobacco, and sunflower cultures.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Agar is not an essential component of the culture medium, but quality and quantity of agar is an important factor that may determine a role in organogenesis.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Commercially available agar may contain impurities.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] With a high concentration of agar, the nutrient medium becomes hard and does not allow the diffusion of nutrients to the growing tissue.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] It influences the organogenesis process by producing adventitious roots, unwanted callus at the base, or senescence of the foliage.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The pH is another important factor that may affect organogenesis route.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The pH of the culture medium is adjusted to between 5.6 and 5.8 before sterilization.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Medium pH facilitates or inhibits nutrient availability in the medium; for example, ammonium uptake in vitro occurs at a stable pH of 5.5 (Thorpe et al., 2008).
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The timing of explant collection significantly impacts regenerative capacity in tissue culture systems, with seasonal variations playing a crucial role in organ formation success.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This phenomenon is clearly demonstrated in *Lilium speciosum*, where bulb scales exhibit differential regenerative responses based on collection season.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Explants harvested during spring and autumn periods readily form bulblets in vitro, while those collected during summer or winter months fail to produce bulblets despite identical culture conditions.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Similar seasonal dependency is observed in *Chlorophytum borivillianum*, a medicinally valuable species that shows markedly enhanced in vitro tuber formation during monsoon seasons compared to other times of year.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This seasonal variation in morphogenic potential likely reflects differences in the physiological state of the source plant, including endogenous hormone levels, carbohydrate reserves, and metabolic activity that fluctuate throughout the annual growth cycle.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Oxygen has a key role in tissue culture, which influences the organ formation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In some cultures, shoot bud formation takes place when the gradient of available oxygen inside the culture vessel is reduced, while induction of roots requires a high oxygen gradient.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Light conditions, including both intensity and spectral quality, function as significant morphogenic signals in plant tissue culture systems.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Spectral composition research has revealed distinct wavelength-dependent responses, with blue light generally promoting shoot organogenesis while red light wavelengths typically favor root induction.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Sequential photoperiod exposure—blue light followed by red light—has been documented to effectively stimulate specific organogenetic pathways in certain species.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The regulatory effect of different wavelengths demonstrates how light quality can selectively control morphogenic outcomes.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Artificial fluorescent lighting produces variable responses depending on the species, promoting root formation in some cultures while inhibiting it in others.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Some species exhibit specialized light requirements, as observed in *Pisum sativum* (garden pea), where shoot bud initiation occurs optimally in darkness before exposure to light stimulates further development.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] For most tissue culture applications, standard lighting protocols typically recommend illumination of approximately 2,000-3,000 lux intensity with a 16-hour photoperiod.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] However, certain species demonstrate exceptional light intensity requirements, exemplified by *Nicotiana tabacum* (tobacco) callus cultures, which require substantially higher light intensities of 10,000-15,000 lux to induce shoot bud formation or somatic embryogenesis.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Temperature serves as a critical environmental factor in plant tissue culture systems, with optimal incubation temperatures varying significantly among species based on their natural habitat requirements.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] While 25 °C represents the standard incubation temperature suitable for many plant species in vitro, species-specific temperature adaptations should be considered to maximize organogenic potential.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Geophytic species from temperate regions typically require lower temperature regimes than the standard protocol.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Notable examples include bulbous plants such as *Galanthus* (snowdrop) which exhibits optimal growth at approximately 15 °C, while certain cultivars of *Narcissus* (daffodil) and *Allium* (ornamental onion) demonstrate enhanced regeneration efficiency at around 18 °C.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Conversely, species of tropical origin generally require elevated temperatures for optimal growth and organogenesis in culture.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Date palm cultures thrive at 27 °C, while *Monstera deliciosa* (Swiss cheese plant) exhibits peak regenerative performance at 30 °C.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] These temperature requirements reflect evolutionary adaptations to the plants' native environmental conditions.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Variation in chromosome number, that is, aneuploidy, polyploidy, etc., in plant cell culture has been well documented in the past.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Chromosome instability of the cells results in gradual decline of morphogenetic potentiality of the callus tissue.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Therefore, to maintain organogenic potential of the callus tissue and the chromosome stability, it is suggested that the time and frequency of subculture should be regularly followed.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Age of culture is often the key to successful organogenesis.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] A young culture/freshly subcultured material may produce organs more frequently than the aged ones.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The probable reason for this is the reduction or loss of the organogenic potential in old cultures.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The ability of cells to undergo organogenesis largely depends on the application of plant growth regulators (PGRs), which influence the developmental direction of the tissue.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The balance between auxins and cytokinins plays a critical role in determining whether shoots or roots will form.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] A lower auxin-to-cytokinin ratio favors shoot regeneration, whereas a higher auxin concentration promotes root formation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] For example, in *Medicago sativa* (alfalfa) cultures, an elevated level of kinetin combined with a low concentration of 2,4-D (a synthetic auxin) leads to shoot development, whereas increasing 2,4-D while reducing kinetin concentration encourages root formation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] However, successful organogenesis is not solely dependent on PGR treatment.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The callus or developing tissue must reach a critical size before organ formation can proceed, reflecting the role of intercellular signaling in coordinating development.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The induction phase in organogenesis represents the transition period between a tissue achieving competence and becoming fully determined to initiate primordia formation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] During this stage, an integrated genetic pathway directs the developmental process before morphological differentiation occurs.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Chemical and physical factors can interfere with genetically programmed developmental pathways and alter morphogenic outcomes.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In *Convolvulus arvensis*, such influences inhibited shoot formation and led instead to callus development.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The conclusion of the induction phase is marked by a cell or group of cells committing to either shoot or root formation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This determination is tested by transferring the tissue from a growth regulator-supplemented medium to a basal medium containing essential minerals, vitamins, and a carbon source but no plant growth regulators.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] At this stage, the tissue completes the induction process and becomes fully determined to its developmental fate.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] A key concept in this process is canalisation, which refers to the ability of a developmental pathway to produce a consistent phenotype despite genetic or environmental variation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] If explants are removed from shoot-inducing medium before canalisation completes, shoot formation drops sharply and root development dominates.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This reflects the morphogenic plasticity of plant tissues *in vitro*.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Morphological differentiation begins in this phase, leading to formation of the nascent organ.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Organogenesis initiation is marked by a shift in cellular polarity, followed by establishment of radial symmetry and growth along the newly defined axis, producing the structural bulge that signals organ initiation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The sequential development of organogenesis can be observed in species such as *Pinus oocarpa Schiede*, where shoot buds are regenerated directly from cotyledons through direct organogenesis.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] However, the specific developmental patterns may vary across different plant species grown in vitro.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The progression of organ formation includes distinct morphological changes, beginning with alterations in surface texture, the emergence of meristemoids, and the expansion of the meristematic region either vertically or horizontally.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This is followed by the protrusion of the meristematic region beyond the epidermal layer, the formation of a structured meristem with visible leaf primordia, and eventually, the full development of an adventitious bud.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] A notable characteristic of in vitro organogenic cultures is the simultaneous formation of multiple meristemoids on a single explant, with varying degrees of differentiation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Within the same explant, buds may exist in different developmental stages, ranging from early initiation to fully developed structures.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Once shoots exceed about 1 cm in length, they are transferred to *in vitro* or *ex vitro* rooting substrates to complete plantlet regeneration.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In direct organogenesis, axillary shoots arise directly from pre-existing meristems at shoot tips and nodes, giving a high multiplication rate.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Because organised shoot meristems rarely accumulate mutations, the resulting plants are genetically uniform and true-to-type - i.e. genetic clones of the parent.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This makes the technique particularly useful for propagation and conservation of economically and environmentally important species.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] However, there are some limitations to organogenesis.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Somaclonal variation, which can result in unwanted genetic diversity, is a potential issue, particularly in the indirect organogenesis process.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Additionally, this technique may not be suitable for recalcitrant plant species, which are those that do not respond well to in vitro culture or regeneration protocols.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] These limitations highlight the need for ongoing research and optimization of methods for different plant species to overcome these challenges in plant propagation and conservation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In addition to growth by cell division, a plant may grow through **cell elongation**.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This occurs when individual cells or groups of cells grow longer.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Not all plant cells grow to the same length.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] When cells on one side of a stem grow longer and faster than cells on the other side, the stem bends to the side of the slower growing cells as a result.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This directional growth can occur via a plant's response to a particular stimulus, such as light (phototropism), gravity (gravitropism), water, (hydrotropism), and physical contact (thigmotropism).
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Plant growth and development are mediated by specific plant hormones and plant growth regulators (PGRs) (Ross et al.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Endogenous hormone levels are influenced by plant age, cold hardiness, dormancy, and other metabolic conditions; photoperiod, moisture, temperature, and other external environmental conditions; and exogenous sources of PGRs, e.g., externally applied and of rhizospheric origin.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Plants exhibit natural variation in their form and structure.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] While all organisms vary from individual to individual, plants exhibit an additional type of variation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Within a single individual, parts are repeated which may differ in form and structure from other similar parts.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This variation is most easily seen in the leaves of a plant, though other organs such as stems and flowers may show similar variation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] There are three primary causes of this variation: positional effects, environmental effects, and juvenility.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] There is variation among the parts of a mature plant resulting from the relative position where the organ is produced.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] For example, along a new branch the leaves may vary in a consistent pattern along the branch.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The form of leaves produced near the base of the branch differs from leaves produced at the tip of the plant, and this difference is consistent from branch to branch on a given plant and in a given species.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The way in which new structures mature as they are produced may be affected by the point in the plants life when they begin to develop, as well as by the environment to which the structures are exposed.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Temperature has a multiplicity of effects on plants depending on a variety of factors, including the size and condition of the plant and the temperature and duration of exposure.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The smaller and more succulent the plant, the greater the susceptibility to damage or death from temperatures that are too high or too low.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Temperature affects the rate of biochemical and physiological processes, rates generally (within limits) increasing with temperature.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Juvenility or heteroblasty is when the organs and tissues produced by a young plant, such as a seedling, are often different from those that are produced by the same plant when it is older.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] For example, young trees will produce longer, leaner branches that grow upwards more than the branches they will produce as a fully grown tree.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In addition, leaves produced during early growth tend to be larger, thinner, and more irregular than leaves on the adult plant.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Specimens of juvenile plants may look so completely different from adult plants of the same species that egg-laying insects do not recognize the plant as food for their young.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The transition from early to late growth forms is sometimes called vegetative phase change.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Plant structures, including, roots, buds, and shoots, that develop in unusual locations are called *adventitious*.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Adventitious roots and buds usually develop near the existing vascular tissues so that they can connect to the xylem and phloem.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] However, the exact location varies greatly.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In young stems, adventitious roots often form from parenchyma between the vascular bundles.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In stems with secondary growth, adventitious roots often originate in phloem parenchyma near the vascular cambium.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In stem cuttings, adventitious roots sometimes also originate in the callus cells that form at the cut surface.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Leaf cuttings of the *Crassula* form adventitious roots in the epidermis.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Adventitious buds develop from places other than a shoot apical meristem, which occurs at the tip of a stem, or on a shoot node, at the leaf axil, the bud being left there during primary growth.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] They may develop on roots or leaves, or on shoots as a new growth.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Shoot apical meristems produce one or more axillary or lateral buds at each node.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] When stems produce considerable secondary growth, the axillary buds may be destroyed.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Adventitious buds may then develop on stems with secondary growth.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Adventitious buds are often formed after the stem is wounded or pruned.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The adventitious buds help to replace lost branches.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Adventitious buds and shoots also may develop on mature tree trunks when a shaded trunk is exposed to bright sunlight because surrounding trees are cut down.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Redwood (*Sequoia sempervirens*) trees often develop many adventitious buds on their lower trunks.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] If the main trunk dies, a new one often sprouts from one of the adventitious buds.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Small pieces of redwood trunk are sold as souvenirs termed redwood burls.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] They are placed in a pan of water, and the adventitious buds sprout to form shoots.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Some plants normally develop adventitious buds on their roots, which can extend quite a distance from the plant.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Shoots that develop from adventitious buds on roots are termed suckers.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] They are a type of natural vegetative reproduction in many species, e.g. many grasses, quaking aspen and Canada thistle.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The Pando quaking aspen grew from one trunk to 47,000 trunks via adventitious bud formation on a single root system.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Some leaves develop adventitious buds, which then form adventitious roots, as part of vegetative reproduction; e.g. piggyback plant (*Tolmiea menziesii*) and mother-of-thousands (*Kalanchoe daigremontiana*).
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The adventitious plantlets then drop off the parent plant and develop as separate clones of the parent.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Coppicing is the practice of cutting tree stems to the ground to promote rapid growth of adventitious shoots.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] It is traditionally used to produce poles, fence material or firewood.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] It is also practiced for biomass crops grown for fuel, such as poplar or willow.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Adventitious rooting may be a stress-avoidance acclimation for some species, driven by such inputs as hypoxia or nutrient deficiency.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Another ecologically important function of adventitious rooting is the vegetative reproduction of tree species such as *Salix* and *Sequoia* in riparian settings.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The ability of plant stems to form adventitious roots is utilised in commercial propagation by cuttings.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Understanding of the physiological mechanisms behind adventitious rooting has allowed some progress to be made in improving the rooting of cuttings by the application of synthetic auxins as rooting powders and by the use of selective basal wounding.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Further progress can be made in future years by applying research into other regulatory mechanisms to commercial propagation and by the comparative analysis of molecular and ecophysiological control of adventitious rooting in 'hard to root' vs.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Adventitious roots and buds are very important when people propagate plants via cuttings, layering, tissue culture.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Plant hormones, termed auxins, are often applied to stem, shoot or leaf cuttings to promote adventitious root formation, e.g., African violet and sedum leaves and shoots of poinsettia and coleus.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Propagation via root cuttings requires adventitious bud formation, e.g., in horseradish and apple.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In layering, adventitious roots are formed on aerial stems before the stem section is removed to make a new plant.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Large houseplants are often propagated by air layering.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Adventitious roots and buds must develop in tissue culture propagation of plants.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The genetics behind leaf shape development in *Arabidopsis thaliana* has been broken down into three stages: The initiation of the leaf primordium, the establishment of dorsiventrality, and the development of a marginal meristem.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Leaf primordium is initiated by the suppression of the genes and proteins of the class I *KNOX* family (such as *SHOOT APICAL MERISTEMLESS*).
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] These class I KNOX proteins directly suppress gibberellin biosynthesis in the leaf primodium.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Many genetic factors were found to be involved in the suppression of these genes in leaf primordia (such as *ASYMMETRIC LEAVES1,* *BLADE-ON-PETIOLE1*, *SAWTOOTH1*, etc.).
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Thus, with this suppression, the levels of gibberellin increase and leaf primorium initiates growth.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Flower development is the process by which angiosperms produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, the flower.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The latter phase has been modelled using the *ABC model*, which describes the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is «determined», which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Plants use floral form, flower, and scent to attract different insects for pollination.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Certain compounds within the emitted scent appeal to particular pollinators.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] In *Petunia hybrida*, volatile benzenoids are produced to give off the floral smell.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] While components of the benzenoid biosynthetic pathway are known, the enzymes within the pathway, and subsequent regulation of those enzymes, are yet to be discovered.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] To determine pathway regulation, *P. hybrida* Mitchell flowers were used in a petal-specific microarray to compare the flowers that were just about to produce the scent, to the *P. hybrida* cultivar W138 flowers that produce few volatile benzenoids. cDNAs of genes of both plants were sequenced.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The results demonstrated that there is a transcription factor upregulated in the Mitchell flowers, but not in the W138 flowers lacking the floral aroma.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] To determine expression of ODO1 throughout the day, RNA gel blot analysis was done.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] The gel showed that ODO1 transcript levels began increasing between 1300 and 1600 h, peaked at 2200 h and were lowest at 1000 h.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] These ODO1 transcript levels directly correspond to the timeline of volatile benzenoid emission.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Additionally, the gel supported the previous finding that W138 non-fragrant flowers have only one-tenth the ODO1 transcript levels of the Mitchell flowers.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Thus, the amount of ODO1 made corresponds to the amount of volatile benzenoid emitted, indicating that ODO1 regulates benzenoid biosynthesis.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Additional genes contributing to the biosynthesis of major scent compounds are OOMT1 and OOMT2.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] OOMT1 and OOMT2 help to synthesize orcinol O-methyltransferases (OOMT), which catalyze the last two steps of the DMT pathway, creating 3,5-dimethoxytoluene (DMT).
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] DMT is a scent compound produced by many different roses yet, some rose varieties, like *Rosa* *gallica* and Damask rose *Rosa* *damascene*, do not emit DMT.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] It has been suggested that these varieties do not make DMT because they do not have the OOMT genes.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] However, following an immunolocalization experiment, OOMT was found in the petal epidermis.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] To study this further, rose petals were subjected to ultracentrifugation.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Supernatants and pellets were inspected by western blot.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Detection of OOMT protein at 150,000g in the supernatant and the pellet allowed for researchers to conclude that OOMT protein is tightly associated with petal epidermis membranes.
[src:dicotyledon/adventitious] Such experiments determined that OOMT genes do exist within *Rosa gallica* and Damask rose *Rosa damascene* varieties, but the OOMT genes are not expressed in the flower tissues where DMT is made.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] This means that each plant produces either male flowers (meaning that they have functional stamens) or female flowers (flowers with functional carpels), but not both.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] At any one time, a dioecious plant produces only functionally staminate or functionally carpellate flowers.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Staminate ("male") *Amborella* flowers do not have carpels, whereas the carpellate ("female") flowers have non-functional "staminodes", structures resembling stamens in which no pollen develops.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Plants may change from one reproductive morphology to the other.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] In one study, seven cuttings from a staminate plant produced, as expected, staminate flowers at their first flowering, but three of the seven produced carpellate flowers at their second flowering.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The small, creamy white flowers are arranged in inflorescences borne in the axils of foliage leaves.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The inflorescences have been described as cymes, with up to three orders of branching, each branch being terminated by a flower.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The bracts transition into a perianth of undifferentiated tepals.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The tepals typically are arranged in a spiral, but sometimes are whorled at the periphery.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Carpellate flowers are roughly 3 to 4 millimetres (1⁄8 to 3⁄16 in) in diameter, with 7 or 8 tepals.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] There are 1 to 3 (or rarely 0) well-differentiated staminodes and a spiral of 4 to 8 free (apocarpous) carpels.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Carpels bear green ovaries; they lack a style.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] They contain a single ovule with the micropyle directed downwards.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Staminate flowers are approximately 4 to 5 mm in diameter, with 6 to 15 tepals.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] These flowers bear 10 to 21 spirally arranged stamens, which become progressively smaller toward the center.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The innermost may be sterile, amounting to staminodes.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The stamens bear triangular anthers on short broad filaments.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] An anther consists of four pollen sacs, two on each side, with a small sterile central connective.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The anthers have connective tips with small bumps and may be covered with secretions.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] These features suggest that, as with other basal angiosperms, there is a high degree of developmental plasticity.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Typically, 1 to 3 carpels per flower develop into fruit.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The fruit is an ovoid red drupe (approximately 5 to 7 mm long and 5 mm wide) borne on a short (1 to 2 mm) stalk.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The remains of the stigma can be seen at the tip of the fruit.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The skin is papery, surrounding a thin fleshy layer containing a red juice.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The inner pericarp is lignified and surrounds the single seed.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The embryo is small and surrounded by copious endosperm.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Currently plant systematists accept *Amborella trichopoda* as sister to all other angiosperms.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Thus, the features of early flowering plants can be inferred by comparing derived traits shared by angiosperms other than *Amborella*, and absent in *Amborella*; these traits are presumed to have evolved after the divergence of the *Amborella* lineage.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] One early 20th century idea of "primitive" (i.e. ancestral) floral traits in angiosperms, accepted until relatively recently, is the *Magnolia* blossom model.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] This envisions flowers with numerous parts arranged in spirals on an elongated, cone-like receptacle rather than the small numbers of parts in distinct whorls of more derived flowers.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] In 2005, the Floral Genome Project used chloroplast genes and expressed sequence tags for floral genes to clarify relationships between well-studied model plants such as *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and lineages including *Amborella*, *Nuphar* (Nymphaeaceae), *Illicium*, the monocots, and the eudicots.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The project explicitly included phylogenetically basal angiosperms to generate insights into the genetics of the earliest flowering plants.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The work generated the cladogram shown below.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] This hypothesized relationship of the extant seed plants places *Amborella* as the sister taxon to all other angiosperms, and shows the gymnosperms as a monophyletic group sister to the angiosperms.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] It supports the theory that *Amborella* branched off from the main lineage of angiosperms before the ancestors of any other living angiosperms.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Because of its evolutionary position sister to all other angiosperms, there was support for sequencing the complete genome of *Amborella trichopoda* to serve as a reference for evolutionary studies.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] In 2010, the US National Science Foundation began a genome sequencing effort in *Amborella*, and the draft genome sequence was posted on the project website in December 2013.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The islands of New Caledonia are a biodiversity hot-spot, preserving many early diverging lineages of plants, of which *Amborella* is but one.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] This preservation has been ascribed to climate stability during and since the Tertiary (66 to 3 million years ago), stability that has permitted the continued survival of tropical forests on New Caledonia.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] In contrast, drought conditions dominated the Australian climate towards the end of the Tertiary.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] Current threats to biodiversity in New Caledonia include fires, mining, agriculture, invasion by introduced species, urbanization and global warming.
[src:dicotyledon/amborella] The IUCN conservation status is Least Concern (LC).
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Angiosperms are by far the most diverse group of land plants with 64 orders, 416 families, approximately 13,000 known genera and 300,000 known species.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] They include all forbs (flowering plants without a woody stem), grasses and grass-like plants, a vast majority of broad-leaved trees, shrubs and vines, and most aquatic plants.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Angiosperms are distinguished from the other major seed plant clade, the gymnosperms, by having flowers, xylem consisting of vessel elements instead of tracheids, endosperm within their seeds, and fruits that completely envelop the seeds.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The ancestors of flowering plants diverged from the common ancestor of all living gymnosperms before the end of the Carboniferous, over 300 million years ago.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] In the Cretaceous, angiosperms diversified explosively, becoming the dominant group of plants across the planet.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Agriculture is almost entirely dependent on angiosperms, and a small number of flowering plant families supply nearly all plant-based food and livestock feed.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Rice, maize and wheat provide half of the world's staple calorie intake, and all three plants are cereals from the Poaceae family (colloquially known as grasses).
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Other families provide important industrial plant products such as wood, paper and cotton, and supply numerous ingredients for drinks, sugar production, traditional medicine and modern pharmaceuticals.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Flowering plants are commonly grown for decorative purposes, with certain flowers playing significant cultural roles in many societies.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Many flowering plants are threatened by habitat destruction and by climate change.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Angiosperms are terrestrial vascular plants; like the gymnosperms, they have roots, stems, leaves, and seeds.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] They differ from other seed plants in several ways.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The largest angiosperms are *Eucalyptus* gum trees of Australia, and *Shorea faguetiana*, dipterocarp rainforest trees of Southeast Asia, both of which can reach almost 100 metres (330 ft) in height.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The smallest are *Wolffia* duckweeds which float on freshwater, each plant less than 2 millimetres (0.08 in) across.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Considering their method of obtaining energy, some 99% of flowering plants are photosynthetic autotrophs, deriving their energy from sunlight and using it to create molecules such as sugars.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The remainder are parasitic, whether on fungi (myco-heterotrophic, formerly thought to be saprophytic) like the orchids for part or all of their life-cycle, or on other plants, either wholly like the broomrapes, *Orobanche*, or partially like the witchweeds, *Striga*.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] In terms of their environment, flowering plants are cosmopolitan, occupying a wide range of habitats on land, in fresh water and in the sea.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] On land, they are the dominant plant group in every habitat except for frigid moss-lichen tundra and coniferous forest.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The seagrasses in the Alismatales grow in marine environments, spreading with rhizomes that grow through the mud in sheltered coastal waters.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Some specialised angiosperms are able to flourish in extremely acid or alkaline habitats.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The sundews, many of which live in nutrient-poor acid bogs, are carnivorous plants, able to derive nutrients such as nitrate from the bodies of trapped insects.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Other flowers such as *Gentiana verna*, the spring gentian, are adapted to the alkaline conditions found on calcium-rich chalk and limestone, which give rise to often dry topographies such as limestone pavement.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] As for their growth habit, the flowering plants range from small, soft herbaceous plants, often living as annuals or biennials that set seed and die after one or two growing seasons, to large perennial woody trees that may live for many centuries and grow to many metres in height.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Some species grow tall without being self-supporting like trees by climbing on other plants in the manner of vines or lianas.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The number of species of flowering plants is estimated to be in the range of 250,000 to 400,000.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] This compares to around 12,000 species of moss and 11,000 species of pteridophytes.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The APG system seeks to determine the number of families, mostly by molecular phylogenetics.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] In the 2009 APG III there were 415 families.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The 2016 APG IV added five new orders (Boraginales, Dilleniales, Icacinales, Metteniusales and Vahliales), along with some new families, for a total of 64 angiosperm orders and 416 families.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The diversity of flowering plants is not evenly distributed.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Nearly all species belong to the eudicot (75%), monocot (23%), and magnoliid (2%) clades.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The remaining five clades contain a little over 250 species in total; i.e. less than 0.1% of flowering plant diversity, divided among nine families.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The botanical term "angiosperm", from Greek words *angeíon* (ἀγγεῖον 'bottle, vessel') and *spérma* (σπέρμα 'seed'), was coined in the form "Angiospermae" by Paul Hermann in 1690, including only flowering plants whose seeds were enclosed in capsules.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The term angiosperm fundamentally changed in meaning in 1827 with Robert Brown, when angiosperm came to mean a seed plant with enclosed ovules.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] In 1851, with Wilhelm Hofmeister's work on embryo-sacs, Angiosperm came to have its modern meaning of all the flowering plants including Dicotyledons and Monocotyledons.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] From 1998, the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG) has reclassified the angiosperms, with updates in the APG II system in 2003, the APG III system in 2009, and the APG IV system in 2016.The APG system treats the flowering plants as an unranked clade without a formal Latin name (angiosperms).
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] A formal classification was published alongside the 2009 revision in which the flowering plants rank as the subclass Magnoliidae.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The evolutionary success and rapid diversification of angiosperms are largely attributed to their coevolutionary relationships with animal pollinators, particularly insects, birds, and bats.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Unlike gymnosperms, which rely primarily on wind for pollen dispersal, flowering plants developed specialized traits—such as nectar production, vivid pigmentations, and complex volatile scents—to attract specific floral visitors.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] This mutualism often leads to **pollination syndromes**, where the morphology of a flower evolves to match the anatomy and sensory capabilities of its primary pollinator.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Zuntini and colleagues constructed a tree of some 6,000 flowering plant genera, representing some 60% of the existing genera, on the basis of analysis of 353 nuclear genes in each specimen.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Much of the existing phylogeny is confirmed; the rosid phylogeny is revised.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Fossilised spores suggest that land plants (embryophytes) have existed for at least 475 million years.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] However, angiosperms appeared suddenly and rapidly diversified during the Early Cretaceous (beginning ~130 mya), much later than other major plant groups.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Claimed records of flowering plants prior to this are not widely accepted, as all supposed pre-Cretaceous "flowers" can be explained through being misidentifications of other seed plants.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Furthermore, almost all of these controversial fossils are described in papers co-authored by the researcher Xin Wang, such as the particularly debated *Nanjinganthus*.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Molecular evidence suggests that the ancestors of angiosperms diverged from the gymnosperms during the late Devonian to early Carboniferous, around 371-338 million years ago.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The origin time of the crown group of flowering plants remains contentious.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] By the Late Cretaceous, angiosperms appear to have dominated environments formerly occupied by ferns and gymnosperms.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Large canopy-forming trees replaced conifers as the dominant trees close to the end of the Cretaceous, 66 million years ago.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The radiation of herbaceous angiosperms occurred much later.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Fossils from the Dakota Formation in Kansas suggest that Beetles had already developed a symbiotic relationship with flowering plants such as *Archaeanthus* by the late-Albian.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The characteristic feature of angiosperms is the flower.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Its function is to ensure fertilization of the ovule and development of fruit containing seeds.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] It may arise terminally on a shoot or from the axil of a leaf.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The flower-bearing part of the plant is usually sharply distinguished from the leaf-bearing part, and forms a branch-system called an inflorescence.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Flowers produce two kinds of reproductive cells.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Microspores, which divide to become pollen grains, are the male cells; they are borne in the stamens.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The female cells, megaspores, divide to become the egg cell.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] They are contained in the ovule and enclosed in the carpel; one or more carpels form the pistil.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The flower may consist only of these parts, as in wind-pollinated plants like the willow, where each flower comprises only a few stamens or two carpels.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] In insect- or bird-pollinated plants, other structures protect the sporophylls and attract pollinators.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The individual members of these surrounding structures are known as sepals and petals (or tepals in flowers such as *Magnolia* where sepals and petals are not distinguishable from each other).
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The outer series (calyx of sepals) is usually green and leaf-like, and functions to protect the rest of the flower, especially the bud.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The inner series (corolla of petals) is, in general, white or brightly colored, is more delicate in structure, and attracts pollinators by colour, scent, and nectar.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Most flowers are hermaphroditic, producing both pollen and ovules in the same flower, but some use other devices to reduce self-fertilization.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Heteromorphic flowers have carpels and stamens of differing lengths, so animal pollinators cannot easily transfer pollen between them.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Homomorphic flowers may use a biochemical self-incompatibility to discriminate between self and non-self pollen grains.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Dioecious plants such as holly have male and female flowers on separate plants.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Monoecious plants have separate male and female flowers on the same plant; these are often wind-pollinated, as in maize, but include some insect-pollinated plants such as *Cucurbita* squashes.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Double fertilization requires two sperm cells to fertilise cells in the ovule.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] A pollen grain sticks to the stigma at the top of the pistil, germinates, and grows a long pollen tube.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] A haploid generative cell travels down the tube behind the tube nucleus.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The generative cell divides by mitosis to produce two haploid (*n*) sperm cells.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The pollen tube grows from the stigma, down the style and into the ovary.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] When it reaches the micropyle of the ovule, it digests its way into one of the synergids, releasing its contents including the sperm cells.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The synergid that the cells were released into degenerates; one sperm makes its way to fertilise the egg cell, producing a diploid (2*n*) zygote.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The second sperm cell fuses with both central cell nuclei, producing a triploid (3*n*) cell.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The zygote develops into an embryo; the triploid cell develops into the endosperm, the embryo's food supply.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The ovary develops into a fruit and each ovule into a seed.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] As the embryo and endosperm develop, the wall of the embryo sac enlarges and combines with the nucellus and integument to form the *seed coat*.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The ovary wall develops to form the fruit or pericarp, whose form is closely associated with type of seed dispersal system.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Other parts of the flower often contribute to forming the fruit.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] For example, in the apple, the hypanthium forms the edible flesh, surrounding the ovaries which form the tough cases around the seeds.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Apomixis, setting seed without fertilization, is found naturally in about 2.2% of angiosperm genera.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Some angiosperms, including many citrus varieties, are able to produce fruits through a type of apomixis called nucellar embryony.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Sexual selection is a mechanism of evolution in which members of one sex choose mates of the other sex (inter-sexual selection), and compete with members of the same sex for access to members of the opposite sex (intra-sexual selection).
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] It is an accepted concept in zoology, but more controversial in botany.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] These two mechanisms are, in theory, the main driving forces of sexual selection in flowering plants and their potential relevance to botany is clear, but more complicated than in zoology.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The complexity of applying the concept of sexual selection to plants arises from the facts that most plants are hermaphrodites and are non-sentient, meaning that the more obvious elements of female choice (e.g. aesthetic judgements on male secondary sexual characteristics) do not apply.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The research challenge currently facing botanists is mainly empirical, namely how significant these processes have actually been in plant evolution.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The masking effect is known as genetic complementation.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Meiosis in flowering plants provides a direct mechanism for repairing DNA through genetic recombination in reproductive tissues.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Sexual reproduction appears to be required for maintaining long-term genomic integrity and only infrequent combinations of extrinsic and intrinsic factors permit shifts to asexuality.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Thus the two fundamental aspects of sexual reproduction in flowering plants, cross-fertilization (outcrossing) and meiosis appear to be maintained respectively by the advantages of genetic complementation and recombinational repair.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Agriculture is almost entirely dependent on angiosperms, which provide virtually all plant-based food and fodder for livestock.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Much of this food derives from a small number of flowering plant families.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] For instance, half of the world's calorie intake is supplied by just three members of the grass family – wheat, rice and maize.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Flowering plants provide a diverse range of materials in the form of wood, paper, fibers such as cotton, flax, and hemp, medicines such as digoxin and opioids, and decorative and landscaping plants.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Coffee and hot chocolate are beverages from flowering plants (in the Rubiaceae and Malvaceae respectively).
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Both real and fictitious plants play a wide variety of roles in literature and film.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Flowers are the subjects of many poems by poets such as William Blake, Robert Frost, and Rabindranath Tagore.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Bird-and-flower painting (*Huaniaohua*) is a kind of Chinese painting that celebrates the beauty of flowering plants.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Flowers have been used in literature to convey meaning by authors including William Shakespeare.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Flowers are used in a variety of art forms which arrange cut or living plants, such as bonsai, ikebana, and flower arranging.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Ornamental plants have sometimes changed the course of history, as in tulipomania.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Many countries and regions have floral emblems; a survey of 70 of these found that the most popular flowering plant family for such emblems is Orchidaceae at 15.7% (11 emblems), followed by Fabaceae at 10% (7 emblems), and Asparagaceae, Asteraceae, and Rosaceae all at 5.7% (4 emblems each).
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Human impact on the environment has driven a range of species extinct and is threatening even more today.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Multiple organizations such as IUCN and Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew suggest that around 40% of plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] The majority are threatened by habitat loss, but activities such as logging of wild timber trees and collection of medicinal plants, or the introduction of non-native invasive species, also play a role.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Relatively few plant diversity assessments have considered climate change, yet it is starting to impact plants as well.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] About 3% of flowering plants are very likely to be driven extinct within a century at 2 °C (3.6 °F) of global warming, and 10% at 3.2 °C (5.8 °F).
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] In worst-case scenarios, half of all tree species may be driven extinct by climate change over that timeframe.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Conservation in this context is the attempt to prevent extinction, whether *in situ* by protecting plants and their habitats in the wild, or *ex situ* in seed banks or as living plants.
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] Some 3000 botanic gardens around the world maintain living plants, including over 40% of the species known to be threatened, as an "insurance policy against extinction in the wild." The United Nations' Global Strategy for Plant Conservation asserts that "without plants, there is no life".
[src:dicotyledon/angiosperms] It aims to "halt the continuing loss of plant diversity" throughout the world.
[src:dicotyledon/apg-iv-system] The **APG IV system** of flowering plant classification is the fourth version of a modern, mostly molecular-based, system of plant taxonomy for flowering plants (angiosperms) being developed by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG).
[src:dicotyledon/apg-iv-system] It was published in 2016, seven years after its predecessor the APG III system was published in 2009, and 18 years after the first APG system was published in 1998.
[src:dicotyledon/apg-iv-system] In 2009, a linear arrangement of the system was published separately; the APG IV paper includes such an arrangement, cross-referenced to the 2009 one.
[src:dicotyledon/apg-iv-system] Compared to the APG III system, the APG IV system recognizes five new orders (Boraginales, Dilleniales, Icacinales, Metteniusales and Vahliales), along with some new families, making a total of 64 angiosperm orders and 416 families.
[src:dicotyledon/apg-iv-system] In general, the authors describe their philosophy as "conservative", based on making changes from APG III only where "a well-supported need" has been demonstrated.
[src:dicotyledon/apg-iv-system] This has sometimes resulted in placements that are not compatible with published studies, but where further research is needed before the classification can be changed.
[src:dicotyledon/apg-iv-system] Like the earlier APG systems, the APG IV revision is based on a phylogenetic tree for the angiosperms, as shown below.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] The **Apiales** are an order of flowering plants, included in the asterid group of dicotyledons.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] Well-known members of Apiales include carrots, celery, coriander, parsley, parsnips, poison hemlock, ginseng, ivies, and pittosporums.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] Apiales consist of seven families, with the type family being the celery, carrot or parsley family, Apiaceae.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] There are seven accepted families within the Apiales, though there is some slight variation and in particular, the Torriceliaceae may also be divided.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] The present understanding of the Apiales is fairly recent and is based upon comparison of DNA sequences by phylogenetic methods.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] The circumscriptions of some of the families have changed.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] In 2009, one of the subfamilies of Araliaceae was shown to be polyphyletic.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] The order Apiales is placed within the asterid group of eudicots as circumscribed by the APG III system.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] Within the asterids, Apiales belongs to an unranked group called the campanulids, and within the campanulids, it belongs to a clade known in phylogenetic nomenclature as Apiidae.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] In 2010, a subclade of Apiidae named Dipsapiidae was defined to consist of the three orders: Apiales, Paracryphiales, and Dipsacales.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] Under the Cronquist system, only the Apiaceae and Araliaceae were included here, and the restricted order was placed among the rosids rather than the asterids.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] The Pittosporaceae were placed within the Rosales, and many of the other forms within the family Cornaceae.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] *Pennantia* was in the family Icacinaceae.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] In the classification system of Dahlgren the families Apiaceae and Araliaceae were placed in the order Ariales, in the superorder Araliiflorae (also called Aralianae).
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] The largest and obviously closely related families of Apiales are Araliaceae, Myodocarpaceae and Apiaceae, which resemble each other in the structure of their gynoecia.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] In this respect however, the Pittosporaceae is notably distinct from them.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] Typical syncarpous gynoecia exhibit four vertical zones, determined by the extent of fusion of the carpels.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] "united bottle-shaped") and symplicate zones are fertile and bear the ovules.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] Each of the first three families possess mainly bi- or multilocular ovaries in a gynoecium with a long synascidiate, but very short symplicate zone, where the ovules are inserted at their transition, the so-called cross-zone (or "Querzone").
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] In gynoecia of the Pittosporaceae, the symplicate is much longer than the synascidiate zone, and the ovules are arranged along the first.
[src:dicotyledon/apiales] Members of the latter family consequently have unilocular ovaries with a single cavity between adjacent carpels.
[src:dicotyledon/aquifoliales] The **Aquifoliales** are an order of flowering plants, including the Aquifoliaceae (holly) family, and also the Helwingiaceae (2-5 species of temperate Asian shrubs) and the Phyllonomaceae (4 species of Central American trees and shrubs).
[src:dicotyledon/aquifoliales] In 2001, the families Stemonuraceae and Cardiopteridaceae were added to this order.
[src:dicotyledon/aquifoliales] This circumscription of Aquifoliales was recognized by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group when they published the APG II system in 2003.
[src:dicotyledon/aquifoliales] In the Cronquist system, there is no Aquifoliales order: the Aquifoliaceae are placed within the order Celastrales and the others are in other families.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] The **dicotyledons**, also known as **dicots** (or, more rarely, **dicotyls**), are one of the two groups into which all the flowering plants (angiosperms) were formerly divided.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] The name refers to one of the typical characteristics of the group: namely, that the seed has two embryonic leaves or cotyledons.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] There are around 200,000 species within this group.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] The other group of flowering plants were called monocotyledons (or monocots), typically each having one cotyledon.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Historically, these two groups formed the two divisions of the flowering plants.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Largely from the 1990s onwards, molecular phylogenetic research confirmed what had already been suspected: that dicotyledons are not a group made up of all the descendants of a common ancestor (i.e., they are not a monophyletic group).
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Rather, a number of lineages, such as the magnoliids and groups now collectively known as the basal angiosperms, diverged earlier than the monocots did; in other words, monocots evolved from within the dicots, as traditionally defined.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] The traditional dicots are thus a paraphyletic group.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] The eudicots are the largest monophyletic group within the dicotyledons.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] They are distinguished from all other flowering plants by the structure of their pollen.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Other dicotyledons and the monocotyledons have monosulcate pollen (or derived forms): grains with a single sulcus.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Contrastingly, eudicots have tricolpate pollen (or derived forms): grains with three or more pores set in furrows called colpi.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Aside from cotyledon number, other broad differences have been noted between monocots and dicots, although these have proven to be differences primarily between monocots and eudicots.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Many early-diverging dicot groups have monocot characteristics such as scattered vascular bundles, trimerous flowers, and non-tricolpate pollen.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] In addition, some monocots have dicot characteristics such as reticulated leaf veins.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Traditionally, the dicots have been called the Dicotyledones (or *Dicotyledoneae*), at any rank.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] If treated as a class, as they are within the Cronquist system, they could be called the Magnoliopsida after the type genus *Magnolia*.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] In some schemes, the eudicots were either treated as a separate class, the Rosopsida (type genus *Rosa*), or as several separate classes.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] The remaining dicots (palaeodicots or basal angiosperms) may be kept in a single paraphyletic class, called Magnoliopsida, or further divided.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Some botanists prefer to retain the dicotyledons as a valid class, arguing its practicality and that it makes evolutionary sense.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] The following lists show the orders in the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group APG IV system traditionally called dicots, together with the older Cronquist system.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Under the Dahlgren and Thorne systems, the subclass name *Magnoliidae* was used for the dicotyledons.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] This is also the case in some of the systems derived from the Cronquist system.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] These two systems are contrasted in the table below in terms of how each categorises by superorder; note that the sequence within each system has been altered in order to pair corresponding taxa.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] There exist variances between the superorders circumscribed from each system.
[src:dicotyledon/dicotyledon] Namely, although the systems share common names for many of the listed superorders, the specific list orders classified within each varies.
